{# ── What I did ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── #}
<div class="flex flex-col gap-6">
  <h3 class="font-avenir font-bold text-2xl">Solving information density.</h3>
  <p class="font-inter text-lg text-muted leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
    Information density posed a big problem with this flow. There was more information
    to parse and more decisions to be made. I solved this with a combination of micro
    interactions, filters and progressive disclosure — allowing patients to dig deeper
    into GP details and available times if they wanted to, or fly through the flow by
    selecting the next available GP and slot.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="flex flex-col gap-6">
  <h3 class="font-avenir font-bold text-2xl">Navigating complex legislation.</h3>
  <p class="font-inter text-lg text-muted leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
    The legislation on this kind of app for SHI GPs was incredibly complex at the
    time. To make sure the flow would work in that environment I ran a series of
    workshops with stakeholders from Clinical, Commercial, Legal and Engineering —
    matching user needs against legal and technical limitations to meet our strategic
    goals.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="flex flex-col gap-6">
  <h3 class="font-avenir font-bold text-2xl">User testing under constraints.</h3>
  <p class="font-inter text-lg text-muted leading-relaxed max-w-2xl">
    User testing was disrupted by COVID-19 and a problem with our usertesting.com
    account. I recruited 9 colleagues and 4 of their contacts to keep the project
    moving. It didn't give me the depth of validation I was after, but it surfaced
    real usability and comprehension issues — particularly valuable as an
    English-speaking designer working on a German-language app.
  </p>
</div>
